Boston <- MASS::Boston
muhat <- mean(Boston$medv)

sehat <- sd(Boston$medv)/sqrt(length(Boston$medv))

SE(\(\hat{\mu}\)) = 0.409

spmedv <- function(data,index) return(coef(lm(medv~1,data=data,subset=index)))

boot(data = Boston,statistic = spmedv,R = 1000)

  1. Ridge regression
set.seed(666)
library(glmnet)

x <- model.matrix(Apps ~ ., train)[,-1] 
x.test <- model.matrix(Apps ~ ., test)[,-1] 
y <- train$Apps
x <- scale(x) 

ridge.mod <- glmnet(x, y, alpha=0)

plot(ridge.mod, xvar='lambda')

## cross-validation
cv.out <- cv.glmnet(x, y, alpha=0, lambda=exp(seq(0, 20, 0.05))) 

ridge.pred <- predict(ridge.mod, s=cv.out$lambda.min, newx=x.test) # prediction
mean((ridge.pred -test$Apps)^2)
## [1] 1.791044e+14

This is a very large test MSE.

  1. LASSO
set.seed(666)
lasso.mod <-glmnet (x,y,alpha =1, lambda =exp(seq(0, 20, 0.05)))
plot(lasso.mod)

cv.out <- cv.glmnet (x,y,alpha =1)
plot(cv.out)

bestlam <- cv.out$lambda.min
lasso.pred <- predict(lasso.mod,s=bestlam ,newx=x.test)
mean((lasso.pred-test$Apps)^2)
## [1] 1.591758e+14

LASSO gives even larger test MSE than ridge.

  1. Comments

In conclusion, for this college dataset, ridge, the Lasso, PCR and PLS didnt win over best subset method. Particularly, shrinkage methods produced much higher test MSE than other methods, because the lambda chosen by these two methods didnt put large penalty on the number of predictors, resulting in a model close to the full model.
